ndia since ancient times", "traits": "Smaller than true aloe (up to 45cm). Grey-green leaves with persistent white spots that remain longer than standard variety. More compact, fan-shaped offsets. Leaves take on brownish-red hue in intense sun.", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Available in humid subtropical climates but often not labeled separately from A. barbadensis. May be found at specialist succulent nurseries."}, {"name": "Aloe arborescens (Krantz Aloe, Candelabra Aloe)", "slug": "aloe-arborescens-krantz-aloe-candelabra-aloe", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "sort_order": 4, "origin": "South Africa (Malawi, Mozambique, Zimbabwe). Cultivated globally since 1700s.", "traits": "Multi-headed branching shrub reaching 1.8-2.4m (6-8ft) tall. Narrow, tooth-edged leaves 15-22cm long in loose rosettes on woody stems. Grey-green foliage.", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Widely available in humid subtropical climates at nurseries like Garden Express, Daleys Fruit, and local garden centers. Popular ornamental hedge plant."}, {"name": "Aloe arborescens ''Variegata''", "slug": "aloe-arborescens-variegata", "lineage_type": "hybrid", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "sort_order": 5, "origin": "Cultivar of A. arborescens. Royal Horticultural Society Award of Garden Merit winner.", "traits": "Variegated leaves with cream/white striping. Same growth habit as species (1.8-2.4m tall).", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "", "availability": "Specialty nurseries in humid subtropical climates. Less common than standard green form."}, {"name": "Aloe ferox (Cape Aloe, Bitter Aloe)", "slug": "aloe-ferox-cape-aloe-bitter-aloe", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "sort_order": 6, "origin": "South Africa (Cape Province, Eastern Cape, KwaZulu-Natal). Cultivated for medicinal use since 1700s.", "traits":