owers, large woody pods", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Precocious, heavy cropping in subtropical areas", "growing_notes": "EXCELLENT FOR humid subtropical climates SUBTROPICAL. Species: Pachira insignis/glabra (NOT true chestnut - Malvaceae family). Tolerates frost inland from Bundaberg. Grown successfully in humid subtropical climates area. Frost-free location preferred. Full sun to partial shade. Well-drained soil. Requires frequent watering. Not a true chestnut but produces edible nuts after proper preparation.", "availability": "Daley''s Fruit Tree Nursery, tropical plant nurseries"}, {"name": "WATER CHESTNUTS - TRADITIONAL INDIAN CULTIVATION", "slug": "water-chestnuts-traditional-indian-cultivation", "lineage_type": "indigenous", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "sort_order": 0, "origin": "", "traits": "", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "", "availability": ""}, {"name": "Singhara / Singara (Water Chestnut) 🏆", "slug": "singhara-singara-water-chestnut", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "sort_order": 1, "origin": "Indigenous to India - traditional crop in Bihar, West Bengal, Jharkhand, tropical monsoon climates backwaters", "traits": "Aquatic floating plant, grows in ponds/wetlands, black/green horned nuts with 2-4 spines", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "4-12 tonnes/hectare. Bihar Large Red: 7 t/ha. Green Spineless: up to 12 t/ha", "growing_notes": "Species: Trapa natans (Lythraceae - aquatic annual, NOT a tree). EXCELLENT FOR tropical monsoon climates WETLANDS/BACKWATERS. Indigenous traditional Indian crop. Grows in tropical/subtropical freshwater. Called ''cooling food'' - beats summer heat. Used medicinally (anti-diabetic, anti-inflammatory). Thrives in monsoon. Farmers grow fish for half year, then water chestnuts. pH 6.7-8.2 ideal. Planted at monsoon beginning. Traditional Ayurvedic use. Made into flour, used fresh. Perfectly adapted to Tropical monsoon wetland agriculture. Can be integrated with traditional paddy field/backwater farming systems.", "availability": ""}, {"name": "Chinese Water Chestnut", "slug": "chinese-water-chestnut", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "sort_order": 2, "origin": "China, Southeast Asia, grown in parts of India", "traits": "Rush-like plant, produces underground tubers (corms), brown chestnut-colored skin", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Good yields in suitable wetlands", "growing_notes": "Species: Eleocharis dulcis (Cyperaceae - sedge/rush, grows tubers). SUITABLE for tropical monsoon climates aquatic cultivation. Grows in freshwater ponds. Different from Singhara (Trapa) - this is tuber not nut. Used extensively in Asian cooking. Crisp texture retained when cooked. High in fiber. Good for tropical wetland farming.", "availability": "Asian vegetable suppliers, specialty aquatic plant nurseries"}, {"name": "Indian Chestnut (Java Olive)", "slug": "indian-chestnut-java-olive", "lineage_type": "indigenous", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "sort_order": 3, "origin": "Native to India, Southeast Asia. Indigenous to tropical monsoon climates and Western Ghats", "traits": "Large tropical deciduous tree, big leathery leaves, unique star-shaped fruit pods", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Good tropical producer", "growing_notes": "Species: Sterculia foetida (Malvaceae family). EXCELLENT FOR tropical monsoon climates/tropical monsoon climates. Indigenous to India including tropical monsoon climates. Perfectly adapted to tropical monsoon climate. Fast-growing, drought-resistant after establishment. Pest-resistant. Valuable timber (durable wood). Traditional medicine use (bark, leaves, seeds - Ayurvedic). Seeds edible after roasting. Used in local cuisines. Thrives in Tropical monsoon heat and humidity. Important reforestation tree. Soil conservation (extensive roots). Cultural significance - gathering spot, sometimes sacred. Well-adapted to monsoon rainfall patterns.", "availability": "Greenverz, tropical monsoon climates Forest Department nurseries, Indian native plant suppliers"}, {"name": "Malabar Chestnut (Pachira)", "slug": "malabar-chestnut-pachira", "lineage_type": "indigenous", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "sort_order": 4, "origin": "Central/South America, widely grown in India including tropical monsoon climates, Karnataka, Tamil Nadu (Western Ghats)", "traits": "Evergreen tropical tree (up to 50 ft), glossy dark green leaves, spectacular white flowers, semi-deciduous", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Good tropical producer", "growing_notes": "Species: Pachira insignis/glabra (Malvaceae family). EXCELLENT FOR tropical monsoon climates/tropical monsoon climates. Grown extensively in Western Ghats of tropical monsoon climates, Karnataka, Tamil Nadu. Perfectly adapted to warm tropical climate with plenty of rainfall - ideal for monsoon regions. Best harvested in dry season (ripe fruits). Well-suited to Tropical monsoon conditions. Requires warm climate, can tolerate some frost. Prefers full sun to partial shade. Well-drained soil essential. Used for desserts, snacks. Quality nuts have glossy bright-brown color. Can be stored 2 months cool/dry, or frozen 6 months. Ornamental value (beautiful flowers). Seeds raw not recommended (prepare first).", "availability": "tropical monsoon climates nurseries, Western Ghats plant suppliers, tropical nurseries throughout India"}, {"name": "2. Indian Chestnut (Sterculia foetida) - Native Kerala species", "slug": "2-indian-chestnut-sterculia-foetida-native-kerala-species", "lineage_type": "indigenous", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "sort_order": 5, "origin": "", "traits": "", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "", "availability": ""}, {"name": "3. Malabar Chestnut (Pachira) - Western Ghats cultivation", "slug": "3-malabar-chestnut-pachira-western-ghats-cultivation", "lineage_type": "indigenous", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "sort_order": 6, "origin": "", "traits": "", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "", "growing_notes": "", "availability": ""}], "variety_count": 18}'::jsonb,
