ndian-blood-cherokee-blood-cling", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "sort_order": 17, "origin": "China (pre-11th century), brought to Mexico by Spanish 1500s, cultivated by Cherokee and Creek Native American tribes by 1600s. Despite name, not indigenous to India.", "traits": "Large fruit (up to 25cm diameter), dark crimson/scarlet red skin like beet, distinctive appearance", "flesh_fruit": "Yellow flesh with red streaks reaching to stone, crimson just below skin, clingstone, sweet when ripe with tart undertones, distinctive flavor unlike most peaches", "yield_notes": "High yield, very productive, late season (August), dependable", "growing_notes": "One of oldest heirloom peaches brought to Americas. Grown by Thomas Jefferson at Monticello (planted 1807), one of 38 types still at Monticello. Superior canning peach. Grows easily from seed (rare for peaches). Hardy and disease resistant. Rich in anthocyanins (antioxidants). Historical significance - first peaches Spanish missionaries brought to New World. Fragile when ripe. Self-fertile but needs pollinator (not self-fruitful). Pickles beautifully. Used in breeding programs. Medium-high chill requirement (500+ hours) - NOT suitable for tropical monsoon climates tropical climate.", "availability": "Trees of Antiquity USA, Monticello historic collection"}, {"name": "Elberta", "slug": "elberta", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "sort_order": 18, "origin": "Georgia USA, developed by Samuel H. Rumph, 1875, named for his wife Clara Elberta Moore Rumph, possibly Chinese Cling seedling", "traits": "Large round fruit, golden-yellow skin with crimson blush, attractive appearance", "flesh_fruit": "Yellow flesh, freestone, sweet with delicate flavor, firm texture", "yield_notes": "Exceedingly prolific - one small tree can produce 200 peaches, larger trees more, hardy", "growing_notes": "''QUEEN OF PEACHES'' before Redhaven developed. Most important commercial peach 1875-1940s. Revolutionary for shipping - first peach firm enough for long-distance transport un-iced (trial shipment NY 1875). Adapted to all soils and climates Gulf to Great Lakes, Atlantic to Pacific. Foundation of Georgia peach industry and Michigan''s 1890s industry. Still grown commercially. Poem written about it by Mabel Swartz Withoft 1900s. Historical significance - transformed American peach industry. Requires thinning. Late August/September harvest (California July-August). 600+ chill hours - NOT suitable for tropical monsoon climates.", "availability": "Stark Bros, Grandpa''s Orchard, Trees of Antiquity, heritage nurseries worldwide"}, {"name": "Belle of Georgia (Georgia Belle)", "slug": "belle-of-georgia-georgia-belle", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "sort_order": 19, "origin": "Marshallville Georgia, discovered by Lewis A. Rumph (Samuel Rumph''s uncle), 1870, named for Mrs. Belle Hall, possibly Chinese Cling seedling", "traits": "Large fruit, greenish-yellow skin, creamy white flesh", "flesh_fruit": "White flesh, freestone, firm texture with honeyed sweetness, ''so juicy bathtub good place to eat one'' (1949), excellent flavor", "yield_notes": "Heavy producer, made it prominent peach by end of 19th century", "growing_notes": "", "availability": ""}, {"name": "Redhaven", "slug": "redhaven", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "sort_order": 20, "origin": "Michigan State University, developed by Dr. Stanley Johnston, released 1940, revolutionized eastern peach growing", "traits": "Round medium-sized fruit, red skin, attractive appearance", "flesh_fruit": "Yellow flesh, freestone, sweet flavor, firm texture", "yield_notes": "Very productive, hardy variety, good bacterial spot resistance", "growing_notes": "", "availability": ""}, {"name": "Hiley Belle (Hiley)", "slug": "hiley-belle-hiley", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "sort_order": 20, "origin": "Marshallville Georgia, introduced by Eugene Hiley, 1886", "traits": "White-fleshed peach with golden skin and red blush", "flesh_fruit": "White flesh, good flavor", "yield_notes": "Good producer", "growing_notes": "Heavily planted throughout middle Georgia for several decades alongside Elberta and Belle of Georgia. Part of trio that defined Georgia peach industry late 1800s-early 1900s. Historical importance to American peach culture.", "availability": "Heritage collections, rare"}, {"name": "Carman", "slug": "carman", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "sort_order": 21, "origin": "Historical variety, once favorite of Midwestern and Southern growers", "traits": "White peach, very rare heirloom", "flesh_fruit": "White flesh, bursting with sweetness, melts in mouth", "yield_notes": "Vigorous and productive", "growing_notes": "Extremely rare heirloom that shouldn''t be lost. Grown as ''El Dulce'' in southern California. Every bit as vigorous/productive now as historically. Once favorite white peach of era.", "availability": "Arboreum Company (currently sold out), extremely rare"}, {"name": "J.H. Hale", "slug": "j-h-hale", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "sort_order": 22, "origin": "First fruit tree to receive plant patent, famous historical variety", "traits": "Large fruit", "flesh_fruit": "Yellow flesh, excellent quality", "yield_notes": "Good producer BUT not self-fertile - requires pollinator", "growing_notes": "Historical significance - first plant patent. Only variety that is NOT self-fruitful - must have another variety to pollinate. Important in peach breeding history.", "availability": "Grandpa''s Orchard, heritage nurseries"}, {"name": "Red Rareripe (Morris Red Rareripe)", "slug": "red-rareripe-morris-red-rareripe", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "sort_order": 23, "origin": "Old heirloom, likely grown by Thomas Jefferson at Monticello, multiple named selections (Prince''s, Martin''s, Pratt, Late Red)", "traits": "Small fruit (not surpassing 3.5 inches diameter), red blush sometimes on and under skin", "flesh_fruit": "Described as productive, melting, highly flavored, excellent, superior to supermarket varieties", "yield_notes": "Productive", "growing_notes": "Near-wild variety, grows true from seed (unique for peaches). Hardier than most peaches - survives Zone 5A. Early ripening historically, though ripens September in northern climates. Yellow and white varieties existed (''lemon rareripes''). Grows easily from pits with cold stratification. More tedious to process due to small size but superior flavor. Jefferson recommended 20ft apart for great production and firewood. Hundreds of seedlings possible from dropped fruit.", "availability": "Rare, mainly through seed savers, some heritage collections"}, {"name": "Cresthaven", "slug": "cresthaven", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "sort_order": 24, "origin": "Michigan State University, Dr. Stanley Johnston, released few years after Redhaven 1940s", "traits": "Developed for cold climates", "flesh_fruit": "Yellow flesh, freestone, excellent flavor", "yield_notes": "Good yields, cold hardy", "growing_notes": "Follow-up to Redhaven success. Another heirloom peach from famous ''Haven'' breeding program. Cold climate adaptation. Part of revolution in northern peach growing.", "availability": "Heritage nurseries, cold-climate specialists"}, {"name": "Golden Jubilee", "slug": "golden-jubilee", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "sort_order": 25, "origin": "Bred from Elberta, real heirloom variety", "traits": "Large late yellow peach", "flesh_fruit": "Yellow flesh, sweet rich flavor, good texture", "yield_notes": "Self-fertile, low-chill variety", "growing_notes": "Works well in South. Might be best variety for California and similar climates. Showy pink spring blossoms add ornamental value. Descended from famous Elberta.", "availability": "Arbor Day Foundation, heritage nurseries"}, {"name": "Loring", "slug": "loring", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "sort_order": 26, "origin": "Missouri peach, 1950s+, grown across country", "traits": "Large fruit, pink spring blossoms", "flesh_fruit": "Yellow flesh, good for desserts and canning", "yield_notes": "Good producer, pretty adaptable", "growing_notes": "Sold at orchards in 1990s. Adaptable across country. Ornamental features with edible fruit perfect for edible gardens. Heirloom peach with wide geographic success.", "availability": "Heritage nurseries, Bennett Orchards"}, {"name": "Dixieland", "slug": "dixieland", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "tropical-monsoon", "sort_order": 27, "origin": "USDA introduction to fill void when Elberta passion waned", "traits": "Large fruit, yellow skin with red blush", "flesh_fruit": "White flesh, sweet soft flesh", "yield_notes": "Good producer", "growing_notes": "Excellent for fresh eating or baking. Introduced to maintain peach industry when Elberta popularity declined. White-fleshed heirloom from USDA breeding.", "availability": "Heritage collections"}], "variety_count": 49}'::jsonb,
  variety_count = 49
WHERE species_slug = 'peach'
   OR source_path = 'brainstorm-inbox/import-payloads/peach.json';

