mate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "sort_order": 8, "origin": "USDA Georgia 1922-23 (Brooks x Alley), released 1968", "traits": "Medium-small elongated nuts (67-70/lb), football shaped, slender", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "One of best yielders - highly productive, consistent annual bearer, precocious", "growing_notes": "Excellent for humid subtropical climates subtropical climate. Strong limbs, disease resistant foliage (dark green). Early-mid ripening (October 11). Moderate scab resistance - manageable with standard spray. Bears 5-6 years. Type I pollinator. Watch for black aphids. Outstanding reliable producer.", "availability": "Australian pecan nurseries, recommended variety"}, {"name": "ELLIOTT", "slug": "elliott", "lineage_type": "open_pollinated", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "sort_order": 9, "origin": "Florida seedling 1912, discovered by Henry Elliot", "traits": "Small teardrop-shaped nuts (62+/lb), smooth symmetrical, distinctive shape", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Consistent producer, alternate bearing pattern, quality maintained in heavy years", "growing_notes": "SPECIALTY PECAN - premium pricing. EXCELLENT scab resistance - ideal for humid subtropical climates humid climate. Drought tolerant, disease resistant. Type II pollinator. Pairs with Pawnee, Caddo, Kanza. Sought after by candy makers, chefs. High oil content exceptional flavor. Slow to produce initially but very reliable. Perfect for subtropical Florida/humid subtropical conditions.", "availability": "Australian nurseries, highly recommended for humid subtropical climates"}, {"name": "KANZA", "slug": "kanza", "lineage_type": "hybrid", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "sort_order": 10, "origin": "USDA 1996 (Major x Shoshoni), named after Kanza Nation of Kansas", "traits": "Small round nuts (65-74/lb), attractive, similar appearance to Elliott", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Good mature production, some alternate bearing", "growing_notes": "", "availability": ""}, {"n