ut applications. Requires fungicide in HIGH HUMIDITY areas - humid subtropical climates would need sprays. Little training required - recommended best homeowner tree. Type A pollinator. Fresh flavor best in world. Native pecan flavor quality without hard shell.", "availability": "Specialty nurseries"}, {"name": "NATIVE/WILD PECANS", "slug": "native-wild-pecans", "lineage_type": "heirloom", "climate_slug": "humid-subtropical", "sort_order": 19, "origin": "Indigenous North America - discovered 16th century by European explorers, staple food for Native Americans since ancient times", "traits": "Variable size/shape (70-150/lb typical), thick hard shells, natural genetic diversity tree to tree", "flesh_fruit": "", "yield_notes": "Variable, no irrigation typically, rely on natural rainfall", "growing_notes": "INDIGENOUS HEIRLOOM - oldest pecan type. Algonquin word ''pacane'' = ''nut so hard requires stone to crack''. EXCELLENT disease resistance due to genetic variability. Heat-tolerant (especially Texas natives). Sustainable - no irrigation/fertilizer/spraying. Best for pecan pieces in candies/pralines/pies. Shell thickness natural protection from animals. Flavor superior to clones - stress improves taste. NOT suitable humid subtropical climates (requires sourcing from wild North American trees).", "availability": "NOT available Australia - U.S. wild harvest only (Texas, Missouri)"}], "variety_count": 20}'::jsonb,
